<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia</i> <i>actonii</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>virginensis</i> or <i>Viguiera</i> <i>reticulata</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>salsola</i>, <i>Croton</i> <i>californicus</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>nevadensis</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>microcephala</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Lepidospartum</i> <i>squamatum</i>, <i>Psorothamnus</i> <i>arborescens</i>, <i>Salazaria</i> <i>mexicana</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>dorrii</i> or <i>Stephanomeria</i> <i>pauciflora</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent with annuals seasonally present. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Encelia virginensis</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy; <i>Salvia dorrii</i> may have equal or greater cover (Evens 2000).</li>
		
		<li><i>Encelia virginensis</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy; no other species with greater or equal cover (LaDoux et al. 2013, Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Viguiera reticulata</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover and other shrubs = or < cover in the shrub canopy (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Encelia actonii, E. virginensis</i>, or <i>Viguiera reticulata</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Encelia actonii</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Buck-Diaz and Evens 2011).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Intermittently flooded arroyos, canyons, alluvial fans, road cuts, and other substrates with recent disturbance. Soils are alluvial with cobble and gravel; found particularly on cobbled calcareous substrates in transmontane settings.  </div>
</div>

        
