<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia virginensis</i> and <i>E. actonii</i> are short-lived, drought-deciduous shrubs that grow to 1.5 m tall. Plants reproduce by seeds that are well adapted to wind dispersal. The plants seed in well after wet years, and are early colonizers of sites such as washes, road cuts, recently cleared or burned land, or other disturbances. They depend on off-site seed sources to reestablish after disturbances. Populations increase with disturbance and are replaced in areas lacking recurring disturbance. They are common on rocky uplands and in gravelly or cobbled washes with slow internal drainage or where the water table is near the soil surface. The soils can be encrusted with salt. <i>E. frutescens </i> is closely related and has been considered a variety of <i>E. virginensis </i>(Esser 1993a). Also, <i>E. virginensis </i>ssp. <i>actoni </i>has been used in older botanical manuals for <i> E. actonii</i>.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Viguiera reticulata </i>is a perennial suffrutescent shrub, usually with several stems from the base. The leaves are net-veined and significantly larger than the related <i>V. parishii</i>. Its life history is not well-known, though it likely does not live for long periods and appears to respond favorably to disturbance. It seeds well after wet years and occupies recently disturbed ground such as in washes or road cuts. Recent taxonomic literature considers this taxon a synonym of <i>Bahiopsis reticulata </i>(UCB 2017).<br/>
<br/>
This alliance is locally common in washes where irregular flooding occurs, particularly on cobbled calcareous substrates. Stands typically occur in medium-gradient, rocky arroyos in the desert mountains of the southeastern portions of state. <i>Encelia virginensis </i> and <i>E. actonii</i> commonly occur as associates on uplands in several alliances at middle and upper elevations in California’s hot deserts. Stands are usually on small terraces within or adjacent to the most active parts of washes, especially on calcareous substrates (though not exclusively to them). Stands in the late spring and summer have spectacular shows of their full golden flowers, lining the washes as they radiate from the mountain ranges. <i>Viguiera reticulata </i> stands are typically small (under 0.5 ha) and appear restricted to calcareous substrates (dolomite, limestone, and marble) where irregular flooding occurs, including on small wash terraces. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance was previously two separate alliances in the 2009 version of this manual that have been combined because of overlapping environmental and floristic characteristics (Evens et al. 2014, NatureServe 2016). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
