    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Small seral stands occur in this section in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag). The alliance has been documented in the Great Valley at Sand Ridge Preserve with <i>Encelia actonii </i>(CNPS unpublished survey data).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ab, Ad, Af, Ah, Aj, Al, An-o). Stands are common in the northeastern subsections, including those on rocky calcareous alluvium. Stands occur in the Clark Mountains (Evens 2000) and generally in the central and eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004), in Death Valley National Park, Mojave Desert National Preserve (Evens et al. 2014), and Joshua Tree National Park (LaDoux et al. 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). Stands occur in washes in the lower portions of the White Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). The alliance has been observed on the eastern slopes of the Sierra Nevada near Tehachapi Pass (VegCAMP 2015a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd). Stands have been surveyed near Lake Isabella with <i>Encelia actonii </i>(CNPS unpublished survey data).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands are well developed on the the east side of the Last Chance Range and in the Cottonwood, Funeral, and Panamint mountains, which drain into Death Valley (Thomas et al. 2004, Evens et al. 2014). Wash communities in the Cottonwood Mountains have relatively high cover and density of <i>E. virginensis </i>(Peterson 1984a, 1984b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bl, Bp). Stands occur along washes and on well-drained soils that have been disturbed recently (e.g., along cleared or burned areas including road cuts) in San Jacinto River drainage near Hemet (Buck-Diaz and Evens 2011) and in the western portions of Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (CNPS unpublished survey data).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia virginensis </i>is important forage for desert tortoise and provides a nectar source for native bees and butterflies. It has been used in revegetation projects in disturbed areas (Esser 1993a). OHV activity occurs in some washes where this alliance grows. However, many of the stands in the eastern portion of its range are in remote canyons that receive little recreational activity. </div>
</div>

    

    

